top align=left class=m><span class=title> The birth of a dark lady</span><hr size=1>     	Born in the damp recesses of the Innothule swamp I was.  During the mad flight from the quagmire of Guk after a nearly failed rescue attempt retrieved my mother from the womb of that fetid place. My mother, drained nearly to the point of unconsciousness holding me cradled whilst my father and uncle fought side by side to make time for us to slip deeper into the swamp away from the festering hive of Frogloks, who seems to pour forth in rising numbers.  Tainted green spells rained down on the following horde, while any who seemed to eager and made it ahead of the pack had the misfortune of having their throats silently and viscously being cut to expose dark green blood.  After a long fight, with my mother drawing from her a small Tra skull of the 'Jen to wield a last slew of protective and healing magics we escaped into the humid dark of Feeroot.<br>
    	A week my mother rested in the mountain home Oggok, before becoming fed up with her dark allies inability to properly care for a dark lady of Noble birth.  So it was, that a week and a day from my birth, my father and uncle did escort my mother north into the heights of the Rathe Mountains.  All was well for a time, as side by side the brothers guarded my mother as she chose a path through that dangerous land. It was only in nearing the murky depth of Lake Rathe that things went awry.<br>
    	It was the fourth day in crossing the mountains, and the blue of the lake could be seen from high ground.  The rumble of thunder blasting away as lightening arced around the peaks was a rather grim backdrop to my kin's hurried descent down the slopes.  Only after a particularly shattering blast<br>
had sent boulders and dirt smashing down near us in a mini avalanche did my mother look back with concern.  A hulking monster of a Cyclops was lumbering down the mountain to join battle with what it presumed was an easy mark. With a quick nod, the brothers took action as my mother whisked me back and away from the main conflict.  My father began his deep foreboding chant which would raise the dead into the living world.  As the blood red skeletal figure coalesced from the parted veil to the plane of Hate, my uncle slipped out of sight and mind for the moment only to reappear behind the Cyclops in a stealthy crouch with his AshenWood spear poised to strike.  As the battle commenced, weapons blazing with magical energies, Blood and guts being spilled on the ground as poisonous sorceries met flesh that my mother realized that this was a losing battle.  My fathers pet had succumbed quickly to the Cyclops' hammering blows, leaving the brothers on the knifes edge of death.  As long as her abilities were hampered by keeping me safe, she would be unable to keep my father and uncle alive in such a deadly combat.  She called out to them, commanding that they flee; and reaching out<br>
with all her Hate to her Lord Innoruuk, called down a divine aura to surround her in a halo of blazing evil and then entered into mortal combat with the cyclops one on one.  Meanwhile, my father took me up and fled down the slope.  The powers of Innoruuk singed the mountainside in a unholy glow<br>
as my mother called down his wrath in her fight.  As the tide her healing began to fail, and the grip of death encroached; my mother reached deeply into her self, calling upon her last reserves of energy to weave a magic from the earth to Root the Cyclops, trapping him long enough for her to stumble after my father and uncle.<br>
    	Slipping through the narrow path that led to the shoreline, it was my uncles acute hearing that picked up the danger and warned my father.  It was to late already though, from the shadows stepped three burly Barbarians, decked in raven black scale mail.  Silently my father handed me to my uncle, only stopping to whisper hurried instructions before turning to singly face them all.<br>
    	The grim expression on Fideleo's face said it all.  Vinavia's scream of rage and anguish called down echos that sent ravens flocking for distant lands.  In the distance the rage of battle magic slowly came to a stop at what was known later as Ixnay's sacrifice. <br>
<br>
